# variables and use
 - int n = length of customer
 - int penalty = for count each hour penalty
 - int min_penalty= for minimum penalty
 - int min_hour = minimum hour for min_penalty 

# Approach

 - initialy shop colse at 0th hour coutn penalty for 0th hour 
 - penaly is applide for each 'Y' so total penalty for 0th hour is total accurence of 'Y'
 - and suppose 0th hour penalty is minimum penalty and min_hour=0

-  Now iterate loop from 0 to n)-1 times

- if at i th hour shop is open and i th hour cusromer is present(customers[i-1]=='Y') then penalty will be decrease
- else at i th hour shop is open and i th hour cusromer is not present(customers[i-1]=='N') then penalty will be increase
- now if penaly for close shope at ith hour is less than min_penalty than update min_hour and min_penalty

- return min_hour


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N);

- Space complexity: O(4);
- because 4 variables are used

# C++ Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int bestClosingTime(string customers) 
    {
        int n=customers.length();

        int min_penalty=0;
        int min_hour=0;
        int penalty=0;

        // if shop close at 0th hour
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            if(customers[i]=='Y')
                penalty++;

        }   

        min_penalty=penalty;
        for(int i=1; i<=n; i++)
        {
            if(customers[i-1]=='Y')
                penalty--;
            else
                penalty++;

            if(penalty<min_penalty)
            {
                min_penalty=penalty;
                min_hour=i;
            }    
        } 

        return min_hour;    
    }
};
```

