# Intuition
If we can find the total penalty for keeping our shop open till day i, in $$O(1)$$ time, we can reduce the time complexity by a lot.

# Approach
Have some preprocessing to calculate the cost of keeping the shop closed on all days, and then one by one open the shop and keeping adding or subtracting the penalty from the previous day penalty corresponding to if there were customers or not on the previous day.

# Solution 1 (Using an array to store penalties)
**Time Complexity: $$O(n)$$**
**Space Complexity: $$O(n)$$**

Create an array to store the total penalty incurred to keep the shop open on `day i`. On every iteration, use the penalty information of the previous day to calculate the penalty for opening the shop till `day i`.

# Code

```
int bestClosingTime(string customers) {
        int n=customers.size();
        int totalPenaltyFromFirst=0;
        for(auto c:customers){
            totalPenaltyFromFirst+=(c=='Y' ? 1 : 0);
        } //preprocessing for calculating total penalty for keeping shop closed on all days

        int minHour=0;
        vector<int> penalties(n+1,0);
        penalties[0]=totalPenaltyFromFirst;
        int minPenalty=penalties[0];

        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            penalties[i]=penalties[i-1];
            if(customers[i-1]=='Y'){
                penalties[i]--; // person came on previous day, cost recovered, penalty reduced
            }
            else if(customers[i-1]=='N'){
                penalties[i]++; // person didn't come on previous day, cost beared, penalty increased
            }

            if(penalties[i]<minPenalty){
                minPenalty=penalties[i];
                minHour=i;
                //if today's penalty is less than previous min penalty, update it
            }
        }

        return minHour;
    }
```
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/23a99079-54c1-4a56-b45f-362de22813b0_1693290553.624397.png)



# Solution 2 (Space Optimization on Solution 1)
**Time Complexity: $$O(n)$$**
**Space Complexity: $$O(1)$$**

We need only one variable to dynamically update the penalty on day i, penalty on day before it (`penalty[i-1]`). So, instead of maintaining a whole array, we maintain a variable, `prevPenalty` that keeps the track of the penalty on the previous day.
The hack used is that instead of maintaining the penalty for `day i`, we update previous day's penalty so that at the end of the loop, it automatically holds the penalty for `day i`, which will be used by `day i+1`

# Code

```
int bestClosingTime(string customers) {
        int n=customers.size();
        int totalPenaltyFromFirst=0;
        for(auto c:customers){
            totalPenaltyFromFirst+=(c=='Y' ? 1 : 0);
        } //preprocessing for calculating total penalty for keeping shop closed on all days

        int minHour=0;
        int prevPenalty=totalPenaltyFromFirst;
        int minPenalty=totalPenaltyFromFirst;

        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            if(customers[i-1]=='Y'){
                prevPenalty--; // person came on previous day, cost recovered, penalty reduced
            }
            else if(customers[i-1]=='N'){
                prevPenalty++; // person didn't come on previous day, cost beared, penalty increased
            }

            if(prevPenalty<minPenalty){
                minPenalty=prevPenalty;
                minHour=i;
                //if updated penalty for today is less than previous min penalty, update it
            }
        }
        return minHour;
    }
```
