# Approach
Suppose, you close the shop at xth hour where 0<=x<=n.
Then, the penalty is count of 'N' untill the shop is opened plus count of 'Y' after the shop is closed.

Now, you just have to loop through 0-n and store the first hour which has the minimum penalty.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:$$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int bestClosingTime(string customers) {
        //curN-->>Count of 'N' till which hour the shop is open.
        //curY-->>Count of 'Y' from where shop is closed to the end hour.
        //At any time the penalty is,curP i.e. ()curY+curN).

        int curY=0,curN=0,n=customers.length();
        for(auto ch:customers) if(ch=='Y') curY++;
        int ans,minPenalty=n+1;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
           int curP=curY+curN;
           if(curP<minPenalty){
               minPenalty=curP;
               ans=i;
           }
           if(customers[i]=='N') curN++;
           else curY--;
        }
        if(curN<minPenalty){
            ans=n;
            minPenalty=curN;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

