# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The intuition behind this solution is to iterate through the hours one by one, tracking the penalty incurred if the shop is closed at each hour. The goal is to find the earliest hour at which the shop should be closed to minimize the penalty.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1.	Initialize curPenalty to keep track of the current penalty, starting with the total number of ‘Y’ (customers) in the input string.
2.	Initialize minPenalty to store the minimum penalty encountered, initially set to the current penalty.
3.	Initialize earliestHour to store the hour at which the shop should be closed to incur the minimum penalty, initially set to 0.
4.	Iterate through the input string, updating curPenalty based on whether a customer (‘Y’) arrives or not (‘N’).
5.	After each update of curPenalty, check if it is smaller than minPenalty. If it is, update minPenalty and earliestHour.
6.	Continue this process for all hours, and the value stored in earliestHour at the end will be the optimal closing time to minimize the penalty.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this solution is O(n), where n is the length of the input string customers. This is because we iterate through the string once to calculate the penalty.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of extra space to store variables like curPenalty, minPenalty, and earliestHour, regardless of the input size.

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int BestClosingTime(string customers) {
        int curPenalty = 0;
        int n = customers.Length;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (customers[i] == 'Y') {
                curPenalty++;
            }
        }

        // Start with closing at hour 0, the penalty equals all 'Y' in closed hours.
        int minPenalty = curPenalty;
        int earliestHour = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            char ch = customers[i];

            // If the status in hour i is 'Y', moving it to open hours decrements
            // the penalty by 1. Otherwise, moving 'N' to open hours increments
            // the penalty by 1.
            if (ch == 'Y') {
                curPenalty--;
            } else {
                curPenalty++;
            }

            // Update earliestHour if a smaller penalty is encountered.
            if (curPenalty < minPenalty) {
                earliestHour = i + 1;
                minPenalty = curPenalty;
            }
        }

        return earliestHour;
    }
}
```

