# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The main idea behind this solution is that the penalty at any given hour is equal to the sum of  number of Y's after the closing hour and
number of N's before the closing hour. 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Steps
1- First count the number of Y's in the string
2- Penalty at 0th hour is equal to total number of Y's in the string
3- Take the penalty at 0th hour as Min
4- Traverse the string.If s[i]=="Y" we decrement the number of Y's after the closing hour (nextY)   by else if i>0 and s[i-1]=="N" we increment the number of N's before the closing hour (prevN) by  1.
5- Penalty=prevN+nextY
6 -Compare the Penalty at ith hour with min penalty and store the minimum of the two  values in min variable and the hour value in res variable 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)



# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int bestClosingTime(string s) {
        //count number of Y's 
        int y=0;
        for (int i=0;i<s.length();i++){
            if(s[i]=='Y')
            y++;

        }

        if(y==s.length())
        return s.length();

        if(y==0)
        return 0;

        //Penalty at 0th hour is equal to number of Y's in the string
        //Taking a the penalty at 0th hour as minimum penalty and comparing it with penalties at different position

        int min=y;

        //nextY stores the number of Y's after the closing hour
        //prevN stores the number of N's before the closing hour
        //Penalty=nextY+prevN
        //Compare the Penalty at ith position and min and storing the value in min variable 

        int nextY=y,prevN=0,res=0;
        for (int i=0;i<s.length();i++){
            if(s[i]=='Y')
            { 
                nextY=nextY-1;
            }
           if(i>0&&s[i-1]=='N')
            prevN++;

           if(prevN+nextY<min)
          { 
              min=prevN+nextY;
              res=i+1;
          }


        }

        return res;
    }
};
```

