# Intuition
The problem can be thought of as minimizing the score.

As the problem statement describes there are different cases for Y and N and what they are valued as.

The best way to understand this is through an illustration.

![IMG_0704.jpeg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/73b8a6bd-3f2a-4247-9528-8ce0e985b75a_1693308400.080159.jpeg)

from this we can assign values for left and right sides of the divider (close time).

**Left (shop is open)**
- y = 0
- n = 1

**Right (shop is closed)**
- y = 1
- n = 0

This is intuitive as we want to decrease the penalty. 
It is bad when the shop is open and there is no customers.
It is bad when the shop is closed and there is customers. 

Therefore we need to find the point in time which minimizes these penalty conditions

# Approach 1: Intuitive O(n) time O(n) space

**1. Count how many Y and N there is**
- This initial step is crucial as it tells us the initial answers for a close time of 0 or leaving the shop always open
- The penalty for a close time of 0 is every Y 
- The penalty for leaving the shop always open is N

```
input = "YYNY"

yes = 3, no = 1

end = 0
    |YYNY  : 3

end = 3
     YYNY| : 1
```

**2. Calculate the rest**
- this can be done by iterating i from left to right, where i represents when the closing time is
- therefore when a Y moves from the rightside to the left, it decreases our total score
- when a N moves from right to left it increases our score
```
input = "YYNY"

yes = 3, no = 1

end = 0
    |YYNY  : 3

end = 1
    Y|YNY  : 2 (score--)

end = 2
     YY|NY : 1 (score--)

end = 3
     YYN|Y : 2 (score++)

end = 4
     YYNY| : 1 (score--)
```

All of these scores can be stored in an array
```
penaltys = [3,2,1,2,1]
```

**3. Finding the best index**
Through an iteration through the penaltys array construced, we would return the earliest best time to close the sotre. In this case it would be 2, since penaltys[2] has the equal least penalty, but it has the earliest closing time.



# Complexity
**Time complexity: O(n) (where n is the size of input customers array)**
- pass one through customers O(n)
- pass two through customers O(n)
- pass three through penaltys O(n)

total = O(n+n+n) = O(n)

**Space complexity: O(n)**
- we use a vector of size N to store the penalty at each time O(n)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int bestClosingTime(string customers) {
        // count how many yes there is
        int yes = 0;
        for(char c : customers) {
            if(c == 'Y') yes++;
        }
        int no = customers.size() - yes;

        // construct penalties vector to store results
        vector<int> penaltys(customers.size() + 1);

        // fill in start and end positions 
        penaltys[0] = yes;
        penaltys[penaltys.size() - 1] = no;

        // calculate the rest
        int pen = yes;
        for(int i = 0; i < customers.size(); i++) {
            if(customers[i] == 'Y') pen--;
            else pen++;
            penaltys[i + 1] = pen;
        }

        // find the best index
        int best = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < penaltys.size(); i++) {
            if(penaltys[i] < penaltys[best]) best = i;
        }

        return best;

    }
};
```
# Approach 2: Optimized O(n) time O(1) space
- instead of storing the penalty for every score, we only need to know the score of the current position and the best so far.
- This means we can reduce the space complexity to O(1) whilst keeping the approach the exact same
```
class Solution {
public:
    int bestClosingTime(string customers) {
        // count how many yes there is
        int pen = 0;
        for(char c : customers) {
            if(c == 'Y') pen++;
        }

        // store current best index and pen
        int idx = 0;
        int curr_best = pen;

        for(int i = 0; i < customers.size(); i++) {
            // shift end point and change pen
            int new_pen = pen;
            if(customers[i] == 'Y') new_pen--;
            else new_pen++;

            // if new best store res
            if(new_pen < curr_best){
                curr_best = new_pen;
                idx = i + 1;
            } 

            // update the current penalty score for use the next iteration
            pen = new_pen;
        }

        return idx;

    }
};
```

