# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Like it's said in the hints, at any given index, the penalty of closing the shop at that hour is given by:
`no. of N's on the left` + `no. of Y's on the right`
*because if we close the shop at a given hour, then the no. of hours when there were no customers before closing would contribute to the penalty.*
*Also the no. of hours in which customers were present after closing would contribute to the penalty.*
 **Now we just need to minimize the penalty.**

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Iterate the given string and find the count of N's and Y's.
- Now we start iterating from the very start and keep track of the no. of N's on the left and Y's on the right of the index we are currently standing on.
- Add the no. of N's on the left and the sum of Y's on the right and minimize this quantity.
- Store the index `ind` of the element where the above quantity is minimum.
- `ind + 1` will be the answer (in case of 0 based indexing).

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int bestClosingTime(string customers) {
        int yes = 0, no = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<customers.size(); i++){
            if(customers[i]=='Y') yes++;
            else no++;
        }
        int mini = yes;
        int ans = -1;
        int leftNo = 0, rightYes = yes;
        for(int i=0; i<customers.size(); i++){
            if(customers[i]=='Y') rightYes--;
            else leftNo++;
            if(leftNo + rightYes < mini){
                mini = leftNo + rightYes;
                ans = i+1;
            }
        }
        if(ans==-1) ans = 0;
        return ans;
    }
};
```

